@fafhrd91 You mean the api of actix itself? I looked through the code of actix-http and couldn't find a place that actually calls `debug!` for error cases, although I might be missing something.
As for the use case, I think this is a very common case - for example in my case (using diesel):
```rust
fn query_objects(db: web::Data<DB>) -> Result<HttpResponse, Error> {
    let returned = my_collection
        .limit(10)
        .load::<SomeObject>(&db.connection_pool.get()?)?;
    Ok(HttpResponse::Ok().json(returned)
}
```
Without support for error logging, one would have to remember to add logs to every possible invocation of `execute`/`load`/etc., which is of course very easily forgotten, until the error actually happens and you don't have any logs :-(

@vmalloc sorry, i missread issue. seems i forgot to port error logging.

it could be done here https://github.com/actix/actix-web/blob/master/src/middleware/logger.rs#L203
you can get access to error via this method https://github.com/actix/actix-web/blob/master/actix-http/src/response.rs#L98

I'm not seeing any 500 response-code errors logged with log_level set to INFO using actix_web 4.3.1 and actix-http 3.3.1. Is there something I need to do to enable such logging?

```rust
use actix_web::{web, App, HttpResponse, HttpServer};

#[actix_web::main]
async fn main() -> std::io::Result<()> {
    HttpServer::new(|| {
        App::new().service(
            web::resource("/")
                .to(|| async { HttpResponse::InternalServerError().body("bad error") }),
        )
    })
    .bind("127.0.0.1:8080")?
    .run()
    .await?;
    Ok(())
}

// cargo run
// curl 127.0.0.1:8080
// 
// Expected: log output
// Result: no internal server error logged
```
